equation_narrative.headline: C-terminal position encoding drives overwhelming arginine prediction from local sequence context
equation_narrative.story: Position 72 sits at ubiquitin's C-terminus in the conserved LRGG tail motif, two residues before the final glycine. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation dominated by C-terminal position encoding and local sequence context, with minimal structural or co-evolutionary signal (only 4 contacts, 2 co-evolving positions). The logit lens shows volatile early shifts through polar (S at 22.6%), aromatic (Y, H), hydrophobic (L, V, A), and charged (D at 34.5% by L5) residues—reflecting the model's exploration of what chemistry typically appears in C-terminal contexts. The decision crystallizes abruptly at L28-30: arginine surges from 5% to 99.5% as highly specific prediction channels activate, driven by the overwhelming constraint that this exact position in ubiquitin's tail must be arginine.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 are dominated by C-terminal position encoding rather than structural context. With only 4 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions, the model relies heavily on local sequence features. Early attention features (F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 all >44 proj) encode terminal position identity. The logit lens shows extreme volatility with 13 lead changes—S (22.6%) → Y → H → L → D (34.5% at L5) → K → R → A → V → S → V → S → L—reflecting the model testing different chemical characters typical of C-terminal positions. This is NOT prediction uncertainty but rather the representation encoding abstract properties: 'this is a C-terminal position that could accommodate various chemistries.' By L18, features like F18:244 (13.3 proj) begin encoding more specific C-terminal tail constraints.
perception_phase.context_character: C-terminal tail position with minimal structural burial (only 4 contacts) and weak co-evolutionary signal (2 positions). The local sequence context LHLVL[?]LRGG strongly constrains the position through the conserved ubiquitin tail motif, where the -3 position (this site) is universally arginine across species.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: only 4 residues within 8Å—minimal burial constraint compared to typical core positions
Co-evolutionary signal: 2 coupled positions—weak functional coupling suggests local sequence dominates
Local sequence reading: L20 head 19 (1.67 proj) and L21 head 13 (1.64 proj) read adjacent positions in the LRGG tail motif
C-terminal encoding: F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 (all >44 proj) activate strongly, encoding terminal position identity
L9 features: F9:5728 (51.2 proj) encodes abstract C-terminal tail properties

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes dramatically at L28-30. Arginine explodes from 5% (L23) to 34.4% (L28) to 99.5% (L33), while lysine—the only other positively charged candidate—peaks at 27.3% (L29) then collapses to 0.2%. Layer 30 MLP neurons deliver the decisive vote: N30:4126 (0.80 proj for R), N30:1400 (0.69 proj), and N30:3629 (0.63 proj) all fire strongly for arginine. Final layer features F33:3601 (126.4 proj), F33:6423 (118.7 proj), and F33:7063 (118.4 proj) act as high-confidence arginine prediction channels, locking in the answer.
decision_phase.transition: The perception-to-decision boundary occurs at L24-25. Layer 24 shows the first coordinated push toward arginine (3.69 total delta, both attention and MLP), but the representation remains ambiguous with L still leading at 18.2%. Layer 25-27 marks the true transition: MLP neurons begin casting decisive votes (L25 total +1.77, L26 total -1.70 as the model suppresses alternatives), and by L28 arginine takes permanent lead at 34.4%. AA-specific prediction features first appear at L24 (F24:5827 at 19.8 proj) but don't dominate until L30+.

candidates.narrative: Arginine remains near-dormant through the perception phase (4.5% at L23), then detonates in the decision phase. The surge begins at L28 (34.4%) driven by MLP neurons N28:3528 (0.69 proj), N28:1024 (0.62 proj), and N28:1616 (0.57 proj). Layer 30 delivers overwhelming support: N30:4126 (0.80 proj for R, also votes 0.61 for K), N30:1400 (0.69 proj), N30:3629 (0.63 proj). Final layer features F33:3601 (126.4 proj), F33:6423 (118.7 proj), F33:7063 (118.4 proj) act as arginine-specific prediction channels with extreme confidence, reaching 99.48% by L33.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L28 (34.4%), dominant L30 (64.8%), overwhelming L33 (99.5%)
key_evidence: N30:4126 (0.80 proj) — strongest R-voting neuron, also supports K at 0.61
F33:3601 (MLP, 126.4 proj) — highest-confidence R prediction channel
L28-30 MLP surge: 6 neurons with >0.5 proj for R

candidates.narrative: Lysine is arginine's closest chemical analog (both positively charged, similar size) and briefly competes in the decision phase. It peaks at 27.3% at L29, supported by neurons that vote for both charged residues (N30:4126 votes 0.61 for K, 0.80 for R). However, the model's late-layer features are tuned specifically for arginine in this C-terminal context—lysine lacks the specific tail motif recognition. By L33, K collapses to 0.19% as arginine-specific channels dominate.
key_evidence: L8-23: maintains 10-18% as generic 'positive charge' representation
N24:426 (0.29 proj for R, 0.54 for K) — briefly favors K over R
Suppressed L30-33 as R-specific features activate

candidates.narrative: Serine leads at L0 (22.6%) not because the model predicts serine, but because the initial representation encodes 'small polar residue near C-terminus'—a common pattern. The logit lens projects this representation toward S/T. As the model reads local sequence context (LHLVL[?]LRGG), it recognizes this specific position requires a charged residue, not polar. Serine peaks again at L14-20 (14-19%) as the representation temporarily encodes polar character, then fades as charged features dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L0-1 (22.6%), resurges L14-20 (14-19%), eliminated L24+ (<5%)
key_evidence: L0 dominance reflects initial 'small polar C-terminal' encoding
Erased by N10:175 (-0.20 proj, votes for G/A/V instead)
L14-20 resurgence from polar-encoding features, not prediction

candidates.narrative: Leucine's prominence at L3-5 (14.9%) and L22-27 (18-23%) reflects the model encoding the hydrophobic local context (LHLVL[?]L). The representation is consistent with 'surrounded by leucines' rather than predicting leucine itself. This is the model reading what's adjacent, not deciding what belongs here. Leucine briefly leads again at L22 (20.0%) before the decision phase begins, then is rapidly suppressed as charged-residue features activate.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L3-5 (14.9%), resurges L22-27 (20%), eliminated L28+ (<5%)
key_evidence: L3-5 peak reflects local hydrophobic context reading
L22 resurgence (20.0%) is final pre-decision representation state
Suppressed by N27:178 (-0.56 proj, votes 0.60 for L as erasure)

candidates.narrative: Aspartate's spike to 34.5% at L5 reflects the representation encoding 'charged residue' character as the model begins recognizing this position's electrostatic requirements. This is NOT a prediction of aspartate—it's the model's representation becoming charged-leaning. The logit lens projects this toward D (negative) before the model has distinguished positive from negative charge requirements. D fades by L8 as the representation refines toward specifically positive charge.
key_evidence: L5 peak reflects 'charged residue' representation, not D-specific prediction
Represents transition from polar to charged character encoding
Erased as model distinguishes positive vs negative charge requirements

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from polar/small (S at 22.6%) to charged (D at 34.5% L5, K at 17.9% L8). This reflects the model reading local sequence context and recognizing electrostatic requirements. The logit lens volatility (D → K lead change at L8) is NOT prediction uncertainty—it's the representation encoding abstract 'charged residue' character before distinguishing positive from negative. Attention heads begin reading the adjacent arginine at position 74 (part of the RGG tail motif).

The representation oscillates between hydrophobic (A, V, L) and polar (S) character with 8 lead changes, reflecting the model's continued exploration of C-terminal position properties. This volatility indicates weak structural constraints (only 4 contacts) forcing the model to rely on abstract positional encoding. By L23, the representation has settled on L (20.0%) with S (19.5%) and K (9.8%)—a mixed state encoding 'C-terminal position with hydrophobic neighbors but charge requirement.' The MLP at L23 delivers +2.11 delta (N23:1038 votes 0.51 for R, 0.50 for K), preparing for decision.

The decisive commitment occurs here. Arginine surges from 5% (L23) to 34.4% (L28) to 64.8% (L30) as arginine-specific MLP neurons fire: N28:3528 (0.69 proj), N28:1024 (0.62 proj), N28:1616 (0.57 proj) at L28, then N30:4126 (0.80 proj), N30:1400 (0.69 proj), N30:3629 (0.63 proj) at L30. Lysine peaks at 27.3% (L29) but is suppressed by L30 as the model's features distinguish R-specific tail motif recognition from generic positive charge. Layer 30 MLP contributes +1.94 total answer projection despite individual erasure neurons (N30:4820 at -0.78), showing coordinated R-voting dominates.

deep_dives.label: C-terminal encoding L1-9
deep_dives.caption: Layer 1 features F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 (all >44 proj) encode terminal position identity. Layer 9 features F9:5728 (51.2 proj), F9:1281 (47.0 proj) refine this to C-terminal tail properties. These are context-encoding features, not predictions—they represent 'this is a C-terminal position' which the logit lens happens to project toward various small/polar residues.

deep_dives.label: Local sequence attention L20-21
deep_dives.caption: Heads L20:19 (1.67 proj) and L21:13 (1.64 proj) read adjacent positions in the LHLVL[R]LRGG motif. These are local writers gathering information from the conserved tail sequence, contributing to the representation's shift toward charged character before the decision phase begins.

deep_dives.label: MLP perception L12-23
deep_dives.caption: Watch the MLP neurons oscillate between supporting different chemical characters. L12 N12:1454 (0.67 proj for R) provides early R support, but is overwhelmed by erasure neurons. L23 N23:1038 (0.51 proj for R, 0.50 for K) finally tips the representation toward positive charge, setting up the decision phase. Total answer projection fluctuates wildly (-0.91 to +2.25), showing the model hasn't committed yet.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset L24-25
deep_dives.caption: Layer 24 features mark the perception-to-decision boundary. F24:5827 (19.8 proj) is the first strong AA-specific prediction feature. The MLP at L24 contributes -3.24 total (many erasure neurons suppressing alternatives), while attention contributes +3.69 toward R. This is where the model transitions from 'encoding context' to 'casting votes.'

deep_dives.label: MLP decision L28-30
deep_dives.caption: The decisive MLP votes. L28: N28:3528 (0.69 proj for R), N28:1024 (0.62 proj), N28:1616 (0.57 proj) initiate the surge. L29: N29:3922 (0.78 proj), N29:3443 (0.53 proj), N29:575 (0.50 proj) amplify. L30: N30:4126 (0.80 proj), N30:1400 (0.69 proj), N30:3629 (0.63 proj) deliver overwhelming support. Total answer projection: -1.98 (L28), -3.36 (L29), +1.94 (L30)—the negative totals reflect strong erasure of K and other alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels L33
deep_dives.caption: Layer 33 MLP features are extreme-confidence arginine channels. F33:3601 (126.4 proj), F33:6423 (118.7 proj), F33:7063 (118.4 proj), F33:3289 (113.2 proj)—all >110 projection, all from MLP stream. These are highly specific prediction features that fire only when the model is certain this exact position in ubiquitin's tail must be arginine.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts arginine with 99.5% confidence by recognizing position 72's role in ubiquitin's conserved C-terminal tail motif. Despite minimal structural constraints (4 contacts) and weak co-evolutionary signal (2 positions), the local sequence context LHLVL[R]LRGG provides overwhelming evidence through the -3 position's universal conservation as arginine across species. The perception phase (L1-23) shows extreme logit-lens volatility—not prediction uncertainty, but the model encoding abstract C-terminal properties while gathering local sequence information. The decision crystallizes at L28-30 when arginine-specific MLP neurons (N30:4126, N30:1400, N30:3629) recognize the tail motif pattern and activate high-confidence prediction channels (F33:3601 at 126.4 proj). Lysine briefly competes as the chemically similar alternative but lacks the specific motif recognition, collapsing from 27.3% to 0.2% in the final layers.
